note:
In the first test case, one operation can be performed: you can choose $x = 69$ and $y = 42$. Then $\left\lfloor \frac{69}{42} \right\rfloor = 1 = q_1$ and $69 \bmod 42 = 27 = r_1$.
In the second test case, it is impossible to perform any operations, as suitable $x$ and $y$ cannot be found.
In the third test case, three operations can be performed:
•  $x = 42$, $y = 17$: $\left\lfloor \frac{42}{17} \right\rfloor = 2 = q_3$ and $42 \bmod 17 = 8 = r_2$;
•  $x = 41$, $y = 16$: $\left\lfloor \frac{41}{16} \right\rfloor = 2 = q_4$ and $41 \bmod 16 = 9 = r_1$;
•  $x = 20$, $y = 12$: $\left\lfloor \frac{20}{12} \right\rfloor = 1 = q_5$ and $20 \bmod 12 = 8 = r_4$;  After these operations, you'll get arrays $q = [5, 4]$ and $r = [9, 100]$, and there are no more operations you can perform.
